## What to do

**1.** Claim it: `vv assignment-claim {{ assignment_id }}`.

**2.** Ground yourself before you write a word of the check-in. Read the code the Premise touches and the work it depends on, and check the framing against them; where they disagree, the code wins. The body is the situation as its author read it: the facts you check against the code, never a verdict to take on its say-so. This is a Premise, so its goal is in play: press whether this is even the right thing to do, not only how. {% if signed_off %}The operator has signed off on this Premise: they have seen it and agree its framing represents what they meant to be discussing, so you and they start from the same picture of what is under discussion. That is all sign-off settles; it is not their judgement that the goal is right, and a Premise's goal stays yours to press, signed or not.{% else %}No one has put their name to this Premise: an agent most likely wrote it from a request for something related, and the operator may never have seen it, so do not take the body as carrying their intent; it may have missed what they actually asked for.{% endif %} Press hardest where being wrong would cost the most, not where it is easy to confirm. This is your own work: do it, don't narrate it.

**3.** Now write the check-in, and for this turn be the operator reading it, not the agent who did the work. You are running ten to twenty assignments like this one at once, each competing for your zero-sum attention, all serving one coherent Project, and you have seconds for this one before the next is waiting. You scan the bold lead of each item and read into the body under it only when a lead stops you, so the whole of what you must decide has to live in the leads. Open by naming the assignment: its kind and its goal, in the domain's own words as if to someone who has never seen it, before any finding. This is a hard rule, not one keep among several: a finding lands on no one who does not yet hold what it is a finding about, and this opening is the one part a reader with none of your context cannot reconstruct for themselves. Then draft the rest as the check-in you would want handed to you, and read it back from that seat and cut every line that would not change what you do next, every line there only to show you the work got done. The report that you grounded, that the grounding holds, that a check-in follows, is the first to go. Keep what you cannot act without: the places where your judgment would change what the agent produces — each led, in the bold opening of its line, by the call it asks of you, never by the question it answers and never by the ground beneath it, which follows after in a line at most. Then black out all but those bold openings and read what is left: a place your judgment must land that is not there has not reached the operator, and you lift it into the opening rather than add a line to point at it. How many such places there are is whatever the work holds (none, one, or several, never a shape to fill); if it is none, the naming and that you are proceeding is itself a complete check-in. Then wait.

